ðŸ§® Problem Understanding
link: https://codeforces.com/contest/2153/problem/C
You are given n sticks with lengths a1, a2, ..., an.
You need to form a polygon that is:

Symmetrical â€” has at least one axis of symmetry.

Strictly convex â€” all internal angles are < 180Â°.

Non-degenerate â€” forms a proper polygon (not a line).

Your goal:
ðŸ‘‰ Find the maximum possible perimeter of such a polygon.
If no valid polygon exists, print 0.

âš™ï¸ Key Observations

Symmetrical polygons require pairs of equal sides â€” e.g., isosceles triangle, symmetric quadrilateral, etc.

Strictly convex and non-degenerate polygons must satisfy the polygon inequality:

maxÂ side
<
sumÂ ofÂ remainingÂ sides
maxÂ side<sumÂ ofÂ remainingÂ sides

Since symmetry is necessary, we focus on duplicate side lengths.

Each equal pair contributes to the symmetric part of the shape.

If one side remains unpaired, it might serve as the base or center of symmetry.

ðŸ’¡ Approach Summary
Step 1: Sort the Sticks

We sort the array to group equal stick lengths together.

sort(v.begin(), v.end());

Step 2: Pair Equal Sticks

We traverse through the sorted array and:

Whenever we find two equal sticks (v[i] == v[i+1]),
we add both to our â€œpaired sidesâ€ total.

If not, we push it into a separate vector sp for leftover unpaired sticks.

if (v[i] == v[i+1]) {
    psum += 2 * v[i];  // add both to symmetric part
    cnt += 2;
    i += 2;
} else {
    sp.push_back(v[i]);
    i++;
}


Now:

psum â†’ total of all paired sides (guaranteed symmetric part)

sp â†’ single leftover sides (potential to extend symmetry)

Step 3: Handle Base Cases

If there are no pairs (psum == 0), symmetry isnâ€™t possible â†’ output 0.

if (psum == 0) cout << 0 << endl;

Step 4: Try to Add Leftover Sides

Now we try to maximize the perimeter by possibly adding one or two unpaired sides (sp) while keeping polygon valid.

We check two situations:

(a) Adding one leftover side

If the leftover side is smaller than the symmetric perimeter,
it can form a valid polygon with that base.

if (sp[i] < psum)
    final = max(final, sp[i] + psum);

(b) Adding two leftover sides

If two leftover sides are close enough (difference < psum),
they can be added symmetrically around the polygon axis.

if (sp[i] - sp[i-1] < psum)
    final = max(final, sp[i] + psum + sp[i-1]);

Step 5: Handle Edge Case

If thereâ€™s only one symmetric pair (cnt == 2) and we didnâ€™t find any valid additions â†’ output 0.
Otherwise, print the final perimeter.

if (cnt == 2 && final == psum)
    cout << 0 << endl;
else
    cout << final << endl;

ðŸ” Example Walkthrough
Example 1
n = 3
sticks = [5, 5, 7]


Sorted: [5, 5, 7]

Pairs: (5, 5) â†’ psum = 10

Leftover: [7]

Check: 7 < 10 âœ…
â†’ final = 17

âœ… Output: 17

â†’ Isosceles triangle with sides (5, 5, 7).

Example 2
n = 3
sticks = [4, 5, 7]


No pairs â†’ psum = 0

No symmetry possible â†’ Output 0

Example 3
n = 7
sticks = [4, 3, 5, 1, 5, 3, 3]


Sorted: [1, 3, 3, 3, 4, 5, 5]

Pairs: (3,3), (5,5) â†’ psum = 16

Leftover: [1, 3, 4]

Add 3 and 4: both < 16 âœ…
â†’ final = 23

âœ… Output: 23

ðŸ§  Complexity
Step	Complexity
Sorting	O(n log n)
Traversal	O(n)
Overall	O(n log n) per test case

Memory usage: O(n)

ðŸ§¾ Summary of Logic Flow
Input â†’ Sort â†’ Pair equal sides â†’ Calculate psum
        â†“
   If psum == 0 â†’ Output 0
        â†“
   Else try to add leftover sides (maximize perimeter)
        â†“
   Edge case: if only one pair â†’ check validity
        â†“
   Output maximum possible perimeter
final code: 

#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
int main() {
    int t;
    cin>>t;
    while(t--){
        int n; cin>>n;
        vector<int> v(n);
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++) cin>>v[i];
        sort(v.begin(),v.end());
        vector<long long> sp;
        int i=0;
        long long psum=0;
        int cnt=0;
        while(i<n){
            if(i+1<n && v[i]==v[i+1]){
            psum+=2*(v[i]);
            i=i+2;
            cnt+=2;
            }
            else{
                sp.push_back(v[i]);
                i++;
            }
        }
        if(psum==0) cout<<0<<endl;
        else {
            long long final=psum;
            for(int i=0;i<sp.size();i++){
                if(sp[i]<psum){
                    final=max(final,sp[i]+psum);
                }
            }
            for(int i=1;i<sp.size();i++){
                if(sp[i]-sp[i-1]<psum){
                    final=max(final,sp[i]+psum+sp[i-1]);
                }
            }
            if(cnt==2 && final==psum) cout<<0<<endl;
            else cout<<final<<endl;
        }
    }
}

my notes: 
ðŸ§© Logic for Symmetry (from handwritten notes)
Condition 1 â€” Occurrence Pattern

To form a symmetrical polygon, sides must appear in specific occurrence patterns.

Case 1: All occur in even pairs
   e.g.  [1,1,2,2,3,3]  âœ… possible symmetry

Case 2: One odd occurrence
   e.g.  [1,1,2,2,3] â†’ odd side = 3 â†’ possible symmetry with base

Case 3: Two odd occurrences
   e.g.  [1,1,2,3,3,4] â†’ may form symmetry if adjacent sides satisfy polygon rule

Condition 2 â€” Polygon Validity

For any polygon:

LargestÂ side
<
SumÂ ofÂ remainingÂ sides
LargestÂ side<SumÂ ofÂ remainingÂ sides

If all elements have even occurrences, âœ… no need to check further.

If thereâ€™s an odd occurrence, we must verify this condition.

When Only One Odd Occurrence

Let that single unpaired side = n

Then:

ð‘›
<
SumÂ ofÂ allÂ pairedÂ sides
n<SumÂ ofÂ allÂ pairedÂ sides

If this holds â†’ polygon possible.

When Two Odd Occurrences

Let the two unpaired sides be nâ‚ and nâ‚‚, with nâ‚ < nâ‚‚.

Then:

